<DOC><DOCNO> AP880518-0356 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2053EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-FiberCable     05-18 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Fiber Cable,0197</SECOND><HEAD>FCC Approves New Cable Under Atlantic</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Communications Commission onWednesday approved construction of a new fiber optic cable underthe Atlantic Ocean to link the United States and Canada with pointsin Europe and the Mediterranean region.   The cable, known as TAT-9, is due to be put in service in 1991.   It will have the capacity to transmit 80,000 simultaneousconversations _ twice the capacity of another optical fiber cablescheduled to go into service between the United States and Europethis year.   The cable is expected to cost the U.S. carriers and more than 25foreign companies participating in the project about $400 million.   The U.S. carriers, with a combined 38.5 percent stake in theproject, include American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co., MCIInternational, US Sprint, TRT Telecommunications, FTCCCommunications, Comsat Communications Inc. and Western Union WorldCommunications. ATandamp;T owns the largest share at 28.7 percent.   The cable will link points in the United States, Canada, theUnited Kingdom, France and Spain. It also will connect to cablesystems linking Spain and Italy and between Italy, Turkey, Greeceand Israel.</TEXT></DOC>